<p class="drop-cap">Western Christianity has largely forgotten how to fast. The Roman Catholic Church, which once maintained a rigorous fasting discipline, has reduced its requirements to two obligatory fast days per year: Ash Wednesday and Good Friday. Most Protestants have abandoned the practice altogether. Ask the average Western Christian about fasting, and the answer is likely something vague about "giving something up for Lent." Perhaps chocolate, or social media, or beer.</p>

<p>The Eastern Church views these things with gentle bewilderment.</p>

<p>In the East, fasting is not a seasonal novelty. It is a way of life. Eastern Christians fast, on average, nearly half the days of the year. This is not an exaggeration. Between the four major fasting seasons and the weekly Wednesday-Friday fast, approximately 180 to 200 days per year involve some form of dietary discipline. The body is not an afterthought in Eastern spirituality. It is a participant, an ally, and sometimes a battleground.</p>

<h2>The Four Fasting Seasons</h2>

<p>The Eastern Church observes four extended fasting periods, each preparing the faithful for a great feast:</p>

<p><strong>The <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#great-fast">Great Fast</a> (Great Lent)</strong> — seven weeks before <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#pascha">Pascha</a>, the most intense fasting period. The first week is the strictest: some monasteries observe a complete fast on Monday and Tuesday, followed by extremely austere meals the rest of the week. The standard lay discipline involves abstaining from meat, dairy, eggs, fish, wine, and oil. Essentially a vegan diet for the entire period. This is the crucible of the Eastern Christian year.</p>

<p><strong>The Apostles' Fast</strong> — begins the Monday after All Saints Sunday (one week after Pentecost) and continues until the feast of Saints Peter and Paul on June 29. Its length varies depending on the date of Pascha, from as short as a week to as long as six weeks.</p>

<p><strong>The Dormition Fast</strong> — August 1 through 14, preparing for the feast of the Dormition (Falling Asleep) of the Theotokos on August 15. Despite its brevity, this fast is kept with the same strictness as Great Lent.</p>

<p><strong>The Nativity Fast (Advent)</strong> — November 15 through December 24, preparing for the Nativity of Christ. Less strict than Great Lent (fish is permitted on most days) but still a genuine period of discipline and anticipation.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. Basil the Great, On Fasting, 4th century">
  Fasting gives birth to prophets and strengthens the powerful. Fasting makes lawmakers wise. It is a safeguard of the soul, a steadfast companion to the body, a weapon for the valiant, a gymnasium for athletes of the spirit.
</Pullquote>

<h2>Wednesday and Friday</h2>

<p>Beyond the four seasons, Eastern Christians fast every Wednesday and Friday throughout the year (with a few exceptions during feast weeks). Wednesday commemorates Judas's betrayal of Christ. Friday commemorates the Crucifixion. The weekly fast follows the same basic discipline as the longer fasts: no meat, dairy, or eggs, and sometimes no fish, wine, or oil, depending on the strictness observed.</p>

<p>This weekly rhythm creates a constant alternation between discipline and freedom, hunger and satisfaction, cross and resurrection. The body never forgets that it is living inside a story. Wednesday: betrayal. Friday: death. Sunday: resurrection.</p>

<p>The gospel is written not just in books but in the stomach.</p>

