<h2>Fasting as Medicine</h2>

<p>The Eastern understanding of fasting is therapeutic, not juridical. You do not fast to earn God's favor or to pay for sins. You fast because you are sick and fasting is part of the cure. The "sickness" in question is the disordered attachment of the will to bodily pleasures, what the Fathers called the <em>passions</em>. The goal is not the suppression of desire but its <strong>reordering</strong>: learning to desire the right things, in the right measure, at the right time.</p>

<p>St. John Chrysostom insisted that fasting from food without fasting from sin is worthless. A person who keeps a perfect vegan Lent but gossips viciously throughout has missed the point entirely. Conversely, a person whose health prevents strict fasting but who practices patience, generosity, and forgiveness during Lent is truly fasting.</p>

<p>The rules are a framework, not a cage. Pregnant women, the elderly, the ill, and children are expected to modify their fast. The spiritual father or priest helps each person calibrate the discipline to their actual condition. Growth, not performance.</p>

<h2>The Feast That Follows</h2>

<p>And then comes the feast.</p>

<p>This is the part that modern culture, with its year-round access to every food and pleasure, cannot replicate. When you have fasted genuinely, the feast that breaks the fast is transfigured. Not merely enjoyable. <em>Revelatory.</em></p>

<p>The Paschal feast is the supreme example. After seven weeks of increasing austerity, after the long services of Holy Week, after the solemn silence of Great Saturday, the Paschal Vigil erupts into light and song at midnight. And then the fast is broken. The table is loaded with everything that has been forbidden: lamb, cheese, eggs (often the beautiful red-dyed eggs of the Paschal tradition), rich pastries, wine. The contrast with the preceding weeks is overwhelming. The body, which has been disciplined and emptied, now receives abundance, and the abundance means something. It is resurrection made tangible.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. John Chrysostom, Paschal Homily, 4th century">
  The table is full-laden; feast ye all sumptuously. The calf is fatted; let no one go away hungry. All of you, enjoy the feast of faith; all of you, receive the riches of goodness.
</Pullquote>

<p>The same principle operates at every feast throughout the year, though in smaller measure. The Dormition Fast gives way to the joy of August 15. The Nativity Fast gives way to the twelve days of Christmas celebration. Even the weekly fast gives way to the freedom of Saturday and Sunday. Constant rhythm: emptying and filling, cross and resurrection, death and life.</p>

